From the factory: The SUB-2000™ is a semi-automatic rifle chambered for the 9mm Luger. By rotating the barrel upwards and back, the SUB-2000™ rifle can instantly be reduced to a size of 16.25 x 7 inches for ease of storage. The polymer of the weapon is made of an impact modified glass reinforced Zytel. Two integrated Picatinny rails come standard on the SUB-2000™ forend for mounting compatible accessories. The stock includes a single point sling loop attachment, a slot for adding a nylon sling loop (1.25" wide is ideal), and a Picatinny rail on the bottom for adding small accessories. The SUB-2000™ features a push-bolt safety located behind the trigger on the grip assembly. The bolt can be locked in the rear position by cycling the bolt to the rear and rotating the operating handle up into the cutout on the receiver.

title: For Sale:  Ruger Vaquero Birdshead Case Hardened
postcontent: Up for sale is an ultra rare Ruger single action...more on the rare part in a minute.  This is a large frame (original Vaquero), not the current "New Vaquero" model.  The large frame originals are capable of "Ruger only" loads.  It's the blued model with Ruger's faux case hardened frame.  The revolver exhibits a slight turn line on the cylinder from handling but has not been fired outside of the Ruger factory.  The model number is 00511 and the catalog number is BNVBH-453.  Now the backstory on the rare part....Ruger transitioned from the original Vaquero to the new Vaquero late 2004 early 2005 timeframe and stopped making the originals.  Thus gun was made in April of 2010 (based on the spent shell casing that came with it from the factory), 5 years after the end of production and 5 years after Ruger stopped the faux case hardening on their blued single actions.  Furthermore, the notorious Ruger warning label on the barrel was much smaller and on the underside of the barrel.  Prior examples were larger and on the side of the barrel.  After acquiring, I called Ruger to verify the manufacter date.  Between that and the model/catalog number (which were unique to this particular gun), I was able to find out through a few searches this was one of Ruger's parts clean up releases that were only sold through Davidson's, and that there were likely less than 200 or so made.  The late production alone makes it a Ruger collector's object of desire, but the barrel warning label variation puts it over the top.   If interested, feel free to reply with your number.  I'd be happy to text additional pictures, including the factory label showing model/catalog as well as the dated spent casing.    Price is $600
